Solution:

The boston housing dataset has 506 observations and 14 variales.

Variables in order:

  1. CRIM per capita crime rate by town

  2. ZN proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.

  3. INDUS proportion of non-retail business acres per town

  4. CHAS Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)

  5. NOX nitric oxides concentration (parts per 10 million)

  6. RM average number of rooms per dwelling

  7. AGE proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940

  8. DIS weighted distances to five Boston employment centers

  9. RAD index of accessibility to radial highways

  10. TAX full-value property-tax rate per $10,000

  11. PTRATIO pupil-teacher ratio by town

  12. B 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town

  13. LSTAT % lower status of the population

  14. MEDV Median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s

Consider this data in context, what is the response variable of interest?

Solution:

The response variable of interest is MEDV, that is the median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s.

For each predictor, fit a simple linear regression model to predict the response. In which of the models is there a statistically significant association between the predictor and the response? Describe your results.

Solution:

Looking at the summary of all the lm models for all the predictors, there p-values are much less than 0.05. So, we can reject the null hypothesis and say that there is a correlation between all predictors and response variable.

But I believe that might not true because chas is a dummy variable and still the model is predicting strong correlation. We can also look at the plot of chas and say that their is no correlation between chas & medv (median value of homes)

Fit a multiple regression model to predict the response using all of the predictors. Describe your results. For which predictors can we reject the null hypothesis \(H_0: \beta_j = 0\)?

Solution:

After looking the p-values in the model summary, we can say tha p-values of predictor indus and age are not less than 0.05. So we cannot reject the null hypothesis for them. We can reject the null hypothesis for all the other predictors in the data.

How do your results from (3) compare to your results from (4)? Create a plot displaying the univariate regression coefficients from (3) on the x-axis and the multiple regression coefficients from part (4) on the y-axis. Use this visualization to support your response.

Solution:

The univariate regression model, gives the effect of only one variable is on the response variable. On the other hand the multi variate model considers the impact of all the variables and hence the prediction can be better with this type of model. In the graph we can see that 7 predictors coefficient lies between -1 and 1 and hence these have strong correlation between them.

# Taking the co-efficient of the predictors from question(3)

model1 <- append(model1, indus_model$coefficients[2])
